@DATABASE RexCat.guide
@$VER: RexCat.guide 2.2 (14.02.2010)
@AUTHOR AmigaPhil

@NODE "MAIN" "Welcome to RexCat"

     @{b}RexCat 2.2@{ub}


@{b}What it is:@{ub}
RexCat is a method to add (auto-)localization ability to
ARexx scripts.
It consists of 2 new @{" functions " LINK "TECH" 8}, ready to be pasted in
your own scripts, and a tool (@{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0}) which
create/update translation files for them.

@{b}What it is not:@{ub}
RexCat is NOT a catalog compiler for binary applications.
The @{" catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} files used by RexCat also end with a
".catalog" suffix, but they are specific text files that
can be interpreted by ARexx.
Starting with v2.1, RexCat also support @{" IFF catalogs " LINK "IFFC" 0}.



     @{" Introduction  " LINK "INTR" 0} - About RexCat
     @{" Requirements  " LINK "REQS" 0} - System requirements and software needed
     @{" Distribution  " LINK "COPY" 0} - Legal stuff

     @{" Installation  " LINK "INST" 0} - Installing RexCat on your system
     @{" Quickstart    " LINK "FIRS" 0} - Your first catalog file in a few steps

     @{" Localize      " LINK "LOCA" 0} - Prepare your scripts for localization
     @{" Translate     " LINK "TRAN" 0} - Create/update catalog files

     @{" Tools         " LINK "TOOL" 0} - Additional tools
     @{" Reference     " LINK "TECH" 0} - File/function description
     @{" FAQ           " LINK "TIPS" 0} - Read this!

     @{" Authors       " LINK "INFO" 0} - How to contact the Authors
     @{" Thanks to     " LINK "CRED" 0} - Those who helped
     @{" History       " LINK "HIST" 0} - Changes log

@ENDNODE
@NODE "INTR" "Introduction"

INTRODUCTION

Welcome to RexCat, an alternative method to implement localization
support for ARexx scripts.
The @{" functions " LINK "TECH" 8} that do the "magic" use a proprietary @{" catalog " LINK "CATA" 0}
file format, which is in fact a plain text file that can be easily
edited with any text editor.
This method is well suited for scripts because ARexx can find
the translated string to output straight from the original string
(the original string being used as ID); making it probably faster
as well.


Advantages of RexCat:

- Very simple to implement, mostly cut-and-paste job.

- No C knowledge needed; basic knowledge of Rexx is enough.

- No need to load any external library.

- No need to prepare a catalog description (.cd), and a catalog
  translation (.ct) to compile a catalog file,
  @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} can scan a source script and build a @{"catalog" LINK "CATA" 0}
  file ready for translations and usage.

  However, starting with v2.1, RexCat can create the .cd and .ct
  files if you wish to use a real IFF catalog.  In this case,
  MakeRexxCat.rexx will also create a replacement source code
  containing adapted functions.


Weakness:

The @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function can only handle a simple string.

- No back slash escape sequence will be interpreted. A string like
  "first part.\\nsecond \\"part\\"" will just fail because of a clash
  with the double-quotes.
  (That said, when building an IFF catalog, back slash sequences
   supported by locale.library will be honored.  But never use the
   quote enclosing the string inside the string.)

- Escaping double-quote or single-quote with an asterix, or doubling
  the quotes as allowed in ARexx will fail as well for the same
  reason.

- No string/variable substitution. (eg.: %s will be printed as is)
  This has to be handled by the author of the script (see the included
  sprintf.rexx script for an example).

@ENDNODE
@NODE "REQS" "Requirements"

REQUIREMENTS

 - AmigaOS 2.1+ if you wish to use IFF catalogs instead of
   the proprietary @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} format

 - RexxMaster running, and Rx available in the search path

 - a Language environment variable (optional, but recommended)

   To check if Language is already set, type from shell:
   Echo $Language

   If it returns $Language then type (eg. for French localization):
   SetEnv Language "français"
   Copy ENV:Language ENVARC:

 - LOCALE: (recommended)

   To check if a LOCALE: assign exists, type from shell:
   Assign "LOCALE:" Exists

   If it does not already exists, you can create it with:
   Assign >NIL: LOCALE: SYS:Locale

     (you may have to create a "SYS:Locale" directory first, or
      choose another directory.)

   Ensure the same command line is in the SYS:S/Startup-Sequence file.

 - a catalog compiler (like: CatComp, SimpleCat, FlexCat, ...)
   if you wish to create a IFF catalog.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "COPY" "Distribution"

Freeware.

You can use the @{b}tls()@{ub} and the @{b}gettlstext()@{ub} @{" functions " LINK "TECH" 8} as you
want in your own scripts.

Feel free to use and distribute the catalog files created for your
project with @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} as you want.
(If you can contribute a @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} for this package,
 you are welcome.  ;-) )

MakeRexCat.rexx is Copyright © 2010 by AmigaPhil.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "INST" "Installation"

INSTALLATION

You can already start to use the @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} tool from
where you have unarchived this RexCat package.
However, it is recommended to install some files to make them
available system wide.

- @{b}Automatic installation@{ub} using the installer script:

  Just double-click on the Install icon and follow the instructions.


- @{b}Manual installation@{ub}:

  - Open a shell and CD to where you have unarchived RexCat.lha

  - Copy the file 'MakeRexCat.rexx' somewhere on your system search path,
    recommended is REXX:

    COPY MakeRexCat.rexx TO REXX:

  - Ensure the Script protection bit is set:

    PROTECT "REXX:MakeRexCat.rexx" +s

  - Copy the file 'MakeRexCat' (and its icon) somewhere on your system
    search path as well, recommended is SYS:Utilities/

    COPY MakeRexCat MakeRexCat.info TO SYS:Utilities

  - Ensure the Script protection bit is set:

    PROTECT "SYS:Utilities/MakeRexCat" +s

  - Create a RexxCatalogs/<language> directory in LOCALE:
    (where <language> is your prefered language, as usually defined by
     the Language environment variable)

    MAKEDIR LOCALE:RexxCatalogs
    MAKEDIR LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>

  - Copy the catalog files for your language in there:

    COPY RexxCatalogs/<Language>/#? TO LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FIRS" "Quickstart"

Quick overview of the RexCat localization system for ARexx:
create/update your first translation file.

- Double-click on the MakeRexCat icon.  (This is an AmigaDOS script
  to control the main @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} with a few mouse clicks.)

- If the DOS command 'RequestFile' exists, it will open and ask you
  to select an ARexx script to scan.  For a very first usage, the
  file 'MakeRexCat.rexx' will be preselected.  Click 'Ok'.
  (If 'RequestFile' does not exists, you will have to type the ARexx
   script filename - with full path - from Shell.)

- Next, you will be prompted to enter a language for the translations.
  Default is the value of the Language env. variable, or 'english'.
  Just press Enter.  The ARexx script is being scanned for strings
  to translate...

- If a @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} (translation file) already exists for the
  selected language, it will be updated in place from where it has
  been found.
  If it did not exist, it will be created in:
  LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
  Assuming you have selected the 'MakeRexCat.rexx' file to translate,
  open the 'MakeRexCat.rexx.catalog' file with your favorite text
  editor, and start the translation.

  See: @{" Editing a RexCat catalog file " LINK "CATA" 0}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "LOCA" "Localize your scripts"

Here are the steps to prepare your own scripts for localization.

-> First ensure your script does not use one of these reserved:

   - function: @{b}tls@{ub}
   - function: @{b}gettlstext@{ub}
   - stem: @{b}tlstext@{ub}

   The @{b}tlstext.@{ub} stem holds the translation array initialized
   by @{b}gettlstext()@{ub} and queried by @{b}tls()@{ub}.

-> Prepare all strings to translate, making them the argument of the
   @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function.

   Example:
   If you want an instruction to show a result localized to the
   user's language, like: SAY "Hello, world!", replace it with:
   SAY tls("Hello, world!")

-> Add the @{b}tls()@{ub} and @{b}gettlstext()@{ub} @{" functions " LINK "TECH" 8} to your script.

   You can copy the code from the MakeRexCat.rexx file with a
   text editor (scroll bottom of the file), and paste it into
   your script (after all EXIT commands in the main code).

-> Make your script to load a translation file somewhere appropriate
   at the begining of the script, using the @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0}
   function.

   Example:
   CALL gettlstext("italian")

   Example (using the Language env. var.):
   scriptLang = ''
   IF EXISTS('ENV:Language') THEN DO
      IF OPEN('el', 'ENV:Language', 'R') THEN DO
         scriptLang = READLN('el')
         CALL CLOSE('el')
      END
   END
   CALL gettlstext(scriptLang)


You can check which strings are available for translation using
@{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0}.
From Shell, type:

 Rx MakeRexCat.rexx CHECK "Path:To/MyScript.rexx"


When you have finished to fine-tune your script (optimizing the
use of strings), the script is ready for a first @{" translation " LINK "TRAN" 0}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "TRAN" "Creating/updating a catalog file"

At this stage, you can decide to work with the ready-to-use
Rexcat catalog, or to prepare an @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0} instead.



Here is how to make a @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} file for your script.

-> From Shell, type:
   Rx MakeRexCat.rexx "Path:To/MyScript.rexx" "<language>"

   Where <language> is the language of the translations.
   (like "français", or "french" under OS4.x)
   Replace "Path:To/MyScript.rexx" by the real @{b}absolute@{ub}
   path to YOUR script. ;-)

-> After the script has been scanned, a new file has been created in
   LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/MyScript.rexx.catalog

-> Edit that file and start to add the translated strings.
   (See the @{" RexCat catalog file format " LINK "CATA" 0} for guidelines.)


If you later want to update the catalog file, just use the same
command line as in the first step.  @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} will search in
<PROGDIR>RexxCatalogs/<language>/ (where <PROGDIR> is the directory
where the source script is in), or in LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/
for it.  (See also: @{" Search path priorities " LINK "PATH" 0})

Strings that no more need to be translated will be removed.
Newer strings to translate will be followed by a @{b}/*** NEW ***/@{ub} marker.



If you wish to distribute your script with the translation files,
you can copy the "RexxCatalogs/<???>/<YourScriptName>.catalog"
files from LOCALE: to the same directory your script is in.

 (@{b}Note@{ub}: You do not need to add the RexxCatalogs/ dir in your
  package if you plan your script to use IFF catalogs.
  The catalog files in RexxCatalogs/ will be ignored anyway.)

Example, from Shell:

  - Create a "RexxCatalogs/<language>" directory for each language
    in the directory your script is in.
    Example:

    MAKEDIR "Path:To/RexxCatalogs"
    MAKEDIR "Path:To/RexxCatalogs/french"
    MAKEDIR "Path:To/RexxCatalogs/italian"
    ...

  - Copy the files from LOCALE: to your script directory.
    Example:

    COPY "LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/french/MyScript.catalog" "Path:To/RexxCatalogs/french/"
    ...

Eventually, add a customized copy of the @{b}MakeRexCat@{ub} @{" tool " LINK "TOOL" 0} in there.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IFFC" "Creating an IFF catalog"

If you wish your script to use an IFF catalog instead of the own
@{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} file, here are the steps to follow:
("Path:To/MyScript.rexx" used here as an example source script.)


-> Create a Catalog Description file (.cd)

   From Shell, type:
   Rx MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD "Path:To/MyScript.rexx" "<language>"

   Where <language> is the @{b}default built-in@{ub} language of MyScript.rexx.

   The Catalog Description file will be created or updated in
   Path:To/Catalogs/MyScript.rexx.cd

   A file with replacement functions will be created in
   Path:To/MyScript.rexx.code

-> Edit your script, remove the old @{b}tls()@{ub} and @{b}gettlstext()@{ub} functions
   and replace them with the newer ones you can find in
   Path:To/MyScript.rexx.code

-> Create a Catalog Translation (.ct)

   From Shell, type:
   Rx MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECT "Path:To/MyScript.rexx" "<language>"

   Where <language> is the language of the translations.

   The Catalog Translation file will be created in
   Path:To/Catalogs/<language>.ct

   Note that if the file already existed, it is replaced !
   If translations exists in the proprietary .catalog translation
   file, they are filled in the Catalog Translation file; otherwise
   the new (replaced) .ct file has no translated strings at all.

-> Compile the catalog file with your favorite editor.

   Example:
   CatComp "MyScript.rexx.cd" "français.ct" CATALOG "Ram:MyScript.rexx.catalog"

@ENDNODE
@NODE "TOOL" "Other tools"

Other tools provided:

 @{b}MakeRexCat@{ub}

    MakeRexCat is a (IconX launched) AmigaDOS script that simplify
    the use of @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0}, allowing to create or update
    a @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} with a few mouse clicks.

    You can copy this script (and its icon) in your own distribution
    package, but remember to edit it to at least change the name of
    the source script to YOUR script.

    The main configuration option is the @{b}srcfile@{ub} variable.
    It's the name of the source ARexx script to scan.  Path can be
    absolute or relative; in the second case, the path is relative
    to where this MakeRexCat tool was started from.
    The @{b}srcfile@{ub} variable can be left empty.  In that case,
    the user will be prompted to select the source script to use.

    If the default built-in language of your script is not english,
    you can also change the variable @{b}srclang@{ub} accordingly.

 @{b}MakeCD@{ub}

    MakeCD is a (IconX launched) AmigaDOS script to easily run the
    "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD" command and create a Catalog Description
    file.

 @{b}MakeCT@{ub}

    MakeCT is a (IconX launched) AmigaDOS script to easily run the
    "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECT" command and create a Catalog Translation
    file.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "TECH" "Technical details"

@{b}More detailled descriptions@{ub}:

 @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} - Create/update catalog files.

    This is the main ARexx program that scan an ARexx script for
    strings to translate, and build a catalog/description/translation
    file for it.

    ARexx scripts don't need MakeRexCat.rexx for locale support, except
    for 2 functions that can be copied/pasted from its source code.

    @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0} - Load a catalog file.

       This Arexx function load a catalog file and initialize
       the @{b}tlstext.@{ub} array with available translated strings.

    @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} - Translate strings

       This ARexx function returns a translated string indexed
       by the given original string.  If no translation is
       available, the original string is returned instead.



 <source script>.catalog  (@{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0})

    is the plain text file produced by MakeRexCat.rexx that
    contains all the strings available for translation in the
    <source script>, and can be edited to add the corresponding
    translations.


 <source script>.cd

    is a Catalog Description file produced by
    "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD" and intended to be used by a
    catalog compiler to build an @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0}.
    (Please refer to the CatComp doc for a description of the
     Catalog Description file format.)

 <source script>.ct

    is a Catalog Translation file produced by
    "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECT" and intended to be used by a
    catalog compiler to build an @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0}.
    (Please refer to the CatComp doc for a description of the
     Catalog Translation file format.)

 <source script>.code

    is a file produced by "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD" and contains
    the replacement code for tls() and gettlstext() so that the
    source script can make use of an @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0}.



 @{b}Search path priorities@{ub}:

    The default paths that will be used:

    - @{" When updating or creating a .catalog " LINK "PATH" 0} with MakeRexCat.rexx
    - @{" When CHECKing a source script " LINK "PATH" 20} with MakeRexCat.rexx CHECK
    - @{" When loading a .catalog " LINK "PATH" 26} with gettlstext()

    - @{" When creating a Catalog Description " LINK "PATH" 65} with MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD
    - @{" When creating a Catalog Translation " LINK "PATH" 69} with MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECT

@ENDNODE
@NODE "TMRC" "MakeRexCat.rexx"

The ARexx program at the heart of RexCat: MakeRexCat.rexx
---------------------------------------------------------

@{b}NAME@{ub}
     MakeRexCat.rexx -- Scan an ARexx script and create (or update)
                        the needed files to implement locale support
                        in ARexx scripts.

@{b}USAGE@{ub}
     Rx MakeRexCat.rexx [<command>] <arguments>

     <command> is optional.  If given, it MUST be the first argument
               in the command line, and be one of the following
               keywords: CHECK, MAKECD, MAKECT

     <arguments> is required, but depends of the <command> used.
                 With the CHECK command, the default template is:
                   SRCFILE/A,DSTDIR
                 otherwise the template is:
                   SRCFILE/A,LANGUAGE/A,DSTDIR

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
     - By default (no command given), it scans an ARexx script
       specified by SRCFILE and collects all the strings that are used
       as argument for a @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function.  It then creates
       or updates a @{" translation file " LINK "CATA" 0} for the LANGUAGE
       with those strings in the directory specified by DSTDIR.
       If no strings are available for translation, no translation
       file is created.
       If DSTDIR is omitted, a @{" default path " LINK "PATH" 0} is used.
     - With the @{b}CHECK@{ub} command, the ARexx script specified by SRCFILE
       is scanned, and all the strings that are used as argument for
       a @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function are collected.  A ".check" file is created
       in the directory specified by DSTDIR (or a @{" default path " LINK "PATH" 0}) with
       all the strings sorted in reverted alphabetical order, prepended
       by the line number in the source script from where the strings were
       found.
     - With the @{b}MAKECD@{ub} command, the ARexx script specified by SRCFILE
       is scanned, and all the strings that are used as argument for
       a @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function are collected.  A Catalog Description
       file (.cd) is created or updated in the directory specified by
       DSTDIR (or a @{" default path " LINK "PATH" 0}) with those strings.
       An already existing .cd file is updated.
       LANGUAGE here is the built-in default language of the script.
     - With the @{b}MAKECT@{ub} command, the ARexx script specified by SRCFILE
       is scanned, and all the strings that are used as argument for
       a @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function are collected.  A Catalog Translation
       file (.ct) is created or replaced in the directory specified by
       DSTDIR (or a @{" default path " LINK "PATH" 0}) with those strings.
       Available translated string in the proprietary translation file
       are added in this file.

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}
     SRCFILE - @{b}Absolute path@{ub} and name of the ARexx script to scan.
     LANGUAGE - With the @{b}MAKECD@{ub} command, it's the default built-in
                language of SRCFILE.  Otherwise, it's the language for which
                the translation file is targeted.
                @{b}Forbidden@{ub} together with the CHECK command.
     DSTDIR - is the optional directory (@{b}absolute path@{ub}) into where to
              create the output file

@{b}RETURNS@{ub}
     One (or two) file(s) whose type depends of the command used.
     (See @{" Technical details " LINK "TECH" 0})

@{b}NOTES@{ub}
     The name "tlstext" is @{b}reserved@{ub} and used as a stem (array) which
     is @{b}global@{ub} in the source script.

     MakeRexCat.rexx will fail to find a @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function to
     check if it has not this exact syntax:
     - The name of the function, case insensitive : @{b}TLS@{ub},
     - immediately followed by an opening parenthesis : @{b}(@{ub},
     - either a single or a double quote : @{b}'@{ub} or @{b}"@{ub},
     - the string to translate, without @{b}any@{ub} occurence of the quote
       chosen previously,
     - the same quote as before the string to translate,
     - immediately followed by a closing parenthesis : @{b})@{ub}.
     "@{i} immediately followed by @{ui}" means that no other extra character
     or blank space is allowed before.

@{b}EXAMPLES@{ub} From a Shell command line:

     > Rx MakeRexCat.rexx "Work:scripts/MyScript.rexx" "french"

     > Rx MakeRexCat.rexx CHECK "Work:scripts/MyScript.rexx" "RAM:"

@{b}BUGS@{ub}

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
     @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0}
     @{" .catalog file format " LINK "CATA" 0}
     @{" MakeRexCat MakeCD MakeCT Tools " LINK "TOOL" 0}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FGTT" "gettlstext()"

ARexx function: gettlstext()
----------------------------

@{b}NAME@{ub}
     gettlstext -- Load a catalog file

@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}
     LANGUAGE/A

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
     Loads a catalog file for the specified LANGUAGE (or the user's
     prefered language) and initialize the @{b}tlstext@{ub} stem with the
     translations.

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}
     LANGUAGE - a literal or a variable with the language's name
                of the translation file to load

@{b}RETURNS@{ub}
     1 (TRUE) if the translation file was successfully loaded, or
     0 (FALSE) otherwise.

@{b}NOTES@{ub}
     If the original gettlstext() function has been replaced by the
     one produced by "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD", the LANGUAGE input
     is ignored; the @{" RexCat catalogs " LINK "CATA" 0} will be ignored as well.

@{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

     CALL gettlstext("french")

@{b}BUGS@{ub}

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
     @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "FTLS" "tls()"

ARexx function: tls()
---------------------

@{b}NAME@{ub}
     tls -- Return the translation of a given string

@{b}TEMPLATE@{ub}
     TLSSRC/A

@{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
     Gets the TLSSRC compound from the @{b}tlstext@{ub} stem.
     (TLSSRC is used as "ID" to find its translated equivalent.)

@{b}INPUTS@{ub}
     TLSSRC - Literal, the original string to translate.
              The max. length size allowed is 250 chars; a longer
              string will be cut down.

@{b}RETURNS@{ub}
     TLSDST, the translated TLSSRC string, or TLSSRC itself if no
     translation is available or the TLSDST string is empty.

@{b}NOTES@{ub}
     The original string (TLSSRC) @{b}must@{ub} be enclosed within
     the same quote (either single-quote or double-quote);
     that quote is then @{b}forbidden@{ub} anywhere else in the
     string.  Any attempt to escape that quote will just fail.
     The following string will never be translated:

       SAY tls('Hello '' world!')

     tls() can only take @{b}one@{ub} single string, without any
     non-printable character.  The following construction will
     fail and always return "I'm <age> years old.":

       SAY tls("I'm " || age || " years old.")

     There @{b}must@{ub} have @{b}no@{ub} extra characters or blank spaces
     between the function name and the opening parenthesis.
     There @{b}must@{ub} have @{b}no@{ub} blank spaces between the last quote
     and the closing parenthesis of the function.

     Supported ARexx escape sequences @{b}should@{ub} be kept outside
     the strings to translate.  The following construction is safe:

       SAY tls("Hello world!") || "*n" || tls("I'm here!")

@{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

     SAY tls("Hello world! I'm here!")

@{b}BUGS@{ub}

@{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
     @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CATA" "The RexCat catalog file"

The RexCat catalog file is a plain text file created by @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0}
and loaded in a @{" prepared ARexx script " LINK "LOCA" 0} by the @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0} function.

The filename of this file is based on the name of the source ARexx script
for which it has been created, appended with a ".catalog" extension.
Eg.: "MyScript.rexx.catalog"

It is stored in a "RexxCatalogs/<language>/" directory, where <language>
is the language for which the ".catalog" has been created.

Both @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} and the @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0} function scan the catalog
file line by line.  Because of this, each instruction @{b}have@{ub} to fit
on a single line !

 - Empty lines are ignored.
 - Lines starting with "//" or "/*" are seen as comments and ignored as well
   (with the exception of a $VER string in it).
 - Valid lines starting with either "tlssrc =" or "tlsdst =" are interpreted
   by ARexx; adding the pairs of original strings and translated strings to
   the @{b}tlstext@{ub} array.
 - All other lines are seen as invalid and ignored.

When translating (editing the tlsdst lines), either the single-quote or the
double-quote can be used to enclose the string.  That quote @{b}must not@{ub} appear
anywhere else in the string.  The translated string, as well as the
original string, should have a size limited to 250 chars.

You can add any comment to the file, but as soon as MakeRexCat.rexx update it,
the file is rewritten and thus the "extra" lines are lost.
Comments opened with /* can be closed several lines later with a */,
but EACH new lines inside those comments @{b}must@{ub} start with a //.

The first occurence of a valid $VER string inside a comment is interpreted.
Version number is preserved (default is the version of the source script,
or "1.0"); with the revision part auto-incremented by 1 if something has
changed in the catalog (newer strings added or unused strings removed).
The AUTHor comment (after the (date)) will be preserved as well.


@{b}Tip@{ub} to validate a RexCat catalog file:
Run it as an ARexx script.  If nothing happen, that's a good sign nothing
is wrong with it; otherwise you will see ARexx error messages.
Note: For this trick to work, each comment line started with a // must
be enclosed in a proper Arexx comment, inside /* and */.
Example:

 /* First line of comment
 // Second line of comment
 // Last line of comment */

@ENDNODE
@NODE "PATH" "Path priorities"

@{b}Search paths and priorities@{ub}:

-> Without the optional DSTDIR argument, @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} tries to
   update any existing .catalog file (its own custom - plain text -
   @{" catalog file format " LINK "CATA" 0}, not the regular IFF catalogs) found in
   the following default paths:

   1) <PROGDIR>Locale/Catalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
      @{b}Deprecated@{ub} path, but kept for backward compatibility.
      (<PROGDIR> is the directory where <script name> is in.)
   2) <PROGDIR>RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
   3) LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog

   If no .catalog file is found, a new one will be created by default
   (unless the DSTDIR is given) in:

   1) LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
   OR (if the previous path fail):
   2) <PROGDIR>RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog


-> In CHECK mode, and without the optional DSTDIR argument,
   @{" MakeRexCat.rexx " LINK "TMRC" 0} will create a <script name>.check file
   in <PROGDIR>.



-> When loading a .catalog file, @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0} search for it in:

   A) Using the proprietary @{" catalog file format " LINK "CATA" 0} :

      1) LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
      2) <CURDIR>RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
         (<CURDIR> is the directory that is current when
          gettlstext() is called.)
      3) <CURDIR>Locale/Catalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
         @{b}Deprecated@{ub} path, but kept for backward compatibility.
      4) <PROGDIR>RexxCatalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
         (<PROGDIR> is the directory where <script name> is in.)
      5) <PROGDIR>Locale/Catalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog
         @{b}Deprecated@{ub} path, but kept for backward compatibility.

      @{b}Note@{ub}: Starting with v2.1, the gettlstext() function
      will no more search for a custom .catalog in LOCALE:Catalogs/
      This location should be reserved for real IFF catalogs (compiled
      with tools like CatComp, FlexCat, ...).

   B) Using an @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0} (with an adapted gettlstext() function) :

      1) LOCALE:Catalogs/<language>/<script name>.catalog

      @{b}Note1@{ub}: Catalogs in <PROGDIR>Catalogs/ will not be found
      because when a ARexx script is started, <PROGDIR> is the path of
      the Rx command.

      @{b}Note2@{ub}: The language argument given to gettlstext() in
      this case is @{b}ignored@{ub} !

   If no .catalog file is found, nothing bad happen (the function
   returns FALSE), and <script name> falls back to the built-in
   language.



-> Without the optional DSTDIR argument, "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECD" will
   update a Catalog Description in <PROGDIR>Catalogs/<script name>.cd
   and a replacement source code in <PROGDIR><script name>.code


-> Without the optional DSTDIR argument, "MakeRexCat.rexx MAKECT" will
   replace a Catalog Translation in <PROGDIR>Catalogs/<script name>.ct

@ENDNODE
@NODE "TIPS" "FAQ"

@{b}- FAQ -@{ub}

@{b}I wish to contribute a catalog for someone else application.
What do I need ?@{ub}

  It depends if the author of the application is expecting a
  @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} or a @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0}.

  - In case of a RexCat catalog and one catalog (for any language)
    already is available in the package, you do not need anything
    else than a text editor.  Open the existing catalog, change
    the header (the $VER: string and language), and replace the
    strings in the tlsdst lines with strings in your language.
    Send the new file to the author.
    If there is no catalog file provided but you have RexCat
    installed, open a Shell and type MakeRexCat (or double-click
    on SYS:Utilities/MakeRexCat), select the source script, and
    enter the translation language.  A new catalog file will be
    created.

  - In case of a IFF catalog, the author should have provided a
    Catalog Description file (.cd).  Just use a catalog compiler
    like CatComp, FlexCat, SimpleCat, ... to build that catalog.

@{b}I wish to distribute my ARexx script with locale support.
What do I have to include in the package ?@{ub}

  If your script is prepared for the built-in @{" RexCat catalogs " LINK "CATA" 0},
  you can include the available catalogs in a RexxCatalogs/
  subdirectory.  If you plan to have an Install script (installer),
  make it to copy RexxCatalogs/<language>/<YourScript.rexx>.catalog
  to LOCALE:RexxCatalogs/<language>/<YourScript.rexx>.catalog
  (Have a look at the Install script for RexCat.)

  If your script is prepared for using @{" IFF catalogs " LINK "IFFC" 0}, then
  ensure to include a Catalog Description file in the package.
  You can create one with the MakeCD tool.
  You don't need to create any RexxCatalogs/ subdir in your
  distribution package.
  Note that when you update your source code and the catalog
  is to be different then the previous version, you have to
  rebuild a new Catalog Description file AND replace again the
  RexCat @{" functions " LINK "TECH" 8} in the source code.

@{b}Will adding localization support in my ARexx script slow it down ?@{ub}

  Yes and no.
  The initial load of the @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} file by the @{" gettlstext() " LINK "FGTT" 0}
  function can take some times, depending of the size of the file.
  (All the translated strings are loaded in memory.)
  You may find that your script is a bit slower to start, but
  as ARexx scripts are usually a lot smaller than modern binary
  applications, that delay should be acceptable.
  Then, all translations are made almost on-the-fly.
  (Just as if the content of a variable was printed instead of a
   string; you won't notice any difference.)

@{b}Why use a proprietary catalog ?@{ub}

  ARexx allows a compound symbol to have any printable characters,
  including spaces.  That makes a translation very easy in a script:
  TranslatedString = tlstext.OriginalString
  An instruction like SAY tls('Hello world!') does in fact output
  the value of "tlstext.Hello world!"

  The @{" RexCat catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} file created is a plain text file
  containing all the original strings and where you can fill in the
  translated strings with a text editor.  The file is ready to use
  as is, without any additional manipulation.

  However, starting with v2.1, RexCat also support the use of an
  @{" IFF catalog " LINK "IFFC" 0} instead of its own catalog.

@{b}Why a .catalog suffix for a file that is not really a catalog ?@{ub}

  The "proprietary" catalog does indeed not have the same format
  as an IFF catalog; but the ".catalog" suffix tells they both
  have the same purpose.
  To avoid confusion, RexCat's own catalogs are stored in a new
  separate RexxCatalogs/ directory.

@{b}Will RexCat support variable substitution in future ?@{ub}

  Unlikely.
  As it stand now, the RexCat method is simple but fast (see
  previous questions).  Adding algorithm to parse extra arguments
  in the @{" tls() " LINK "FTLS" 0} function will slow the translation process
  significantly; making a localized ARexx script less performant.

  However, if you need to format a string, have a look at the
  included sprintf.rexx script.  ;-)

@{b}Why does MakeRexCat.rexx create its .catalog in LOCALE: by default
instead of PROGDIR ?@{ub}

  ARexx scripts are often tools for other applications.  When a
  developer accept to bundle third parties scripts with his own
  product, he should not have to take the hassle to write an
  appropriate installation program that will handle all the
  @{" .catalog " LINK "CATA" 0} for all the ARexx scripts.
  Without an installation routine, the end user will have many
  .catalog file all over his hard disk, most of them not being
  of any use for him.

  On the other hand, if a contributor wish to distribute himself
  his ARexx script intended for another application, he would have
  to find that application's PROGDIR where to install the
  appropriate catalogs.

  Using LOCALE: as default for RexxCatalogs/ simplify the catalogs
  installation; the path being standard for all installer scripts.

  Cf.: @{" Search paths and priorities " LINK "PATH" 0}

  Anyway, you can change the destination path for the created
  .catalog by using the DSTDIR argument with MakeRexCat.rexx

@{b}Why is the LANGUAGE argument in gettlstext() ignored when
using an IFF catalog ?@{ub}

  It's a limitation of the ARexx host of locale.library :
  the OpenCatalog() function does not allow to be passed a
  specific language for the catalog to load.

@ENDNODE
